Firstly, I‚Äôll start by saying that I‚Äôm a Dominican woman who grew up in Washington Heights going to Dominican restaurants is not a big thing for me and my family because it‚Äôs just a part of our day to day, right? Well- here‚Äôs the thing‚Ä¶El Tina was something of a treasure to us in Washington Heights so when I moved away- I missed my food from El Tina. While walking to the hotel above the Apollo from my yoga class at Method Collective on 12 ave I stumbled across this NEW AND IMPROVED location for TINA in HARLEM ü§©üò©thank God, because it was looking grim for me in the Sunday brunch department. I wanted robust, and flavorful foods that would satisfy me enough to make me ‚Äúclean the plate! My daughter and I ordered our favorites. For her- TRES GOLPES & of course CHICHARRON de cerdo. For myself- I was craving MONDONGO con ARROZ BLANCO. I promise you that it was JUST LIKE MY CHILDHOOD crept back into my life for one Sunday afternoon. For drinks my daughter immediately ordered a MORIR SO√ëANDO ü•∞üò© it was so nice that it wasn‚Äôt sprinkled with cinnamon powder the way unauthentic places tend to do it. I ordered a MODELO ESPECIAL beer and I absolutely PROMISE you that the beer was SO ICE COLD that I was glad I didn‚Äôt have it until after eating all my Mondongo & rice- otherwise I wouldn‚Äôt have had any room for all that delicious food! TEN OUT OF TEN!!! I absolutely recommend!

The plantain was very greasy they gave me most of the plantain ends and pieces of plantains soaked in oil. I was very disappointed.

The chicken was juicy and flavorful!! The rice was slightly bland however the red beans brought it to life with so much flavor. The plantains were a little too thick for my liking however they were very sweet. Definitely will be ordering again.

Nothing is better than a good bowl of Sancocho on a very rainy day and El Tina restaurant is where I decided to go.

The restaurant is small but has ample seating for diners to sit. On entrance, you‚Äôre warmly greeted with a smile. Servers can be seen wearing netting over their hair as they serve the food from a buffet set up. This is a big plus for me.

The food portions are very generous for the price. Equally so, the taste is out of this world and well seasoned. I added a little bit of hot sauce to give my Sancocho a little umph as i like my soups spicy.

Try El Tina if you want good Spanish food and great customer service. You will be treated like family.
